#X text 116 177 LFO rate;
#X text 172 240 range;
#X text 159 503 The filter coefficient is sent to [receive~] objects inside the [pd 2nd.order] subpatches., f 31;
#X text 448 248 To the left \, we have a LFO that controls the filter coefficient. It is a triangular waveform in MIDI pitch converted to Hz and then to the filter coefficient. This is the simplest example of a phaser \, which can have more stages and other features like feedback as we'll see later. Below we have a stereo patch with 16 and 14 stages. Open it., f 45;
#X text 56 79 A typical design is to have 1st-­order allpass filters in cascade with the same center frequency \, but one can experiment with different ones for each. Allpass filters will introduce phase shifts that cancels when mixed to the original input \, so mixing the original and filtered signals controls the depth of notches. The example to the left is based on the H15 Pd example and is we have four 1st-order filters with the same frequency input. We then say this phaser has 4 stages., f 102;
#X text 56 16 The phaser is similar to a flanger as it creates notches in the audio. In both we have a sweeping motion of the notches over time \, but in a flanger always generates evenly spaced notches and is based on comb filtering \, while phasers use allpass filters that promote non-uniformly spaced notches and can be designed to arbitrarily control their location., f 102;
